Russian Communism is making a comeback
Moscow — More than a year ago, while on leave from my teaching position at a university in the United States, I returned to my hometown, Moscow.
My destination was not a stronghold of free speech.
But this place still retained some degree of freedom.
Opposition leader Alexei Navalny had traveled across the country in an attempt to win the support of politicians not under the control of the Kremlin.
The people's protest activities broke out.
Independent non-governmental organizations operate domestically.
Journalists and analysts do not necessarily follow the Kremlin's line.
While the Communist Party is widely seen as a product of history.
Since then, Navalny has been imprisoned, and his protest movement has been suppressed.
The anti-corruption foundation was banned for "extremism," and its members are being exiled or investigated.
Nearly every day, journalists, media outlets, human rights advocates, or independent organizations are added to the "foreign agents" list — even worse — labeled as "undesirable."
In the past year, Russia has been in a non-free state, though not distant, but very intense.
For example, the law on designating foreign agents was enacted in 2012, aimed at undermining or discrediting institutions or individuals engaged in "political activities" while receiving funding from abroad.
But the application of this law has become increasingly arbitrary, to the point where retweeting now can also be a reason for being labeled a foreign agent.
（ The "undesirable" label can lead to complete prohibition.
） As of this year alone, a record 101 entities have been added to the list of foreign agents.
Out of the cumulative total of 359, 88 are media-related organizations and individuals.
According to the Russian government, the aforementioned "agents" must be listed because they "influence national politics."
But the core goal of journalism and propaganda is certainly to influence politics.
And this is precisely the problem: although President Vladimir Putin has positioned himself to continue controlling Russian politics for the foreseeable future, he views criticism as a threat to his survival.
Despite all this silence and persecution, the Communist Party, an unlikely group, has survived and become the only real opposition to the Kremlin.
This is largely due to Navalny's "smart voting" strategy — that is, urging people to support the forces most likely to defeat the Kremlin-backed candidates — and the Communist Party performed very strongly in last month's parliamentary and regional elections.
Official data shows that Communist Party candidates won 18.9% of the votes for the State Duma (parliament), while the Kremlin-backed United Russia party received nearly 49.8%.
But the Communists refused to accept this result, insisting that the vote was manipulated.
In fact, some experts estimate that they should have received about 30% of the votes, while United Russia should have received about 35%.
For many Russians, the Communists now seem more respected than Putin.
But they are no longer the original Communists.
They not only do not deny the pleasures of the world; party members instead wear fur coats, are enthusiastic about traveling abroad, drive foreign cars, and use social media.
Some are millionaires — for example, the charismatic agricultural chief Pavel Groudnikov (who was banned from participating in last month's election).
Although the party is still led by the 77-year-old Gennadiy Zyuganov, it is increasingly influenced and supported by younger members.
Taking Nikolay Bondarlenko as an example.
The 36-year-old Bondarlenko, nicknamed "Red Navalny," severely criticized the poorly designed pension reform of 2018.
Recently, when a regional minister claimed that Russians should be able to "eat better" with a monthly salary of just 3,500 rubles (about $50), Bondarlenko recorded his efforts to prove the minister wrong on his YouTube channel.
Although threatened with disqualification, Bondarlenko was still allowed to participate in the recent State Duma election.
Although he received support from Navalny's "smart voting" system, he still lost to the candidate from United Russia.
But his potential should not be overlooked: recently, he proposed a protest title accusing "the state and government taking over" United Russia.
Then there is 43-year-old Anastasia Yudashova.
Like Bondarlenko, she surprisingly lost the last election.
Yet she remains very — — and increasingly — — popular.
Thanks to the "Smart Voting" system, another rising star, the elegant Yekaterina Ngalicheva, was elected to the Moscow City Duma in 2019.
Ironically, the modernization of the Communist Party reflects people's longing for the past: in 1917, Lenin's Bolsheviks promised justice and equality, and the country that realized these ideals, though strict, was still not devoid of fairness and compassion.
Additionally, like the liberal Navalny, today's Communist Party represents a predictable and consistent vision, in which an individual's eccentricity does not affect everyone.
It is precisely based on this logic that all opponents of the Kremlin are increasingly uniting: forming a "United Russia" that can oppose Putin.
This situation is not limited to Russia alone.
In the recent parliamentary elections in the Czech Republic, Andrej Babiš — also known as Czech Donald Trump — failed to be re-elected as prime minister, as the opposition alliance set aside their ideological differences and formed a common coalition, with its leader Petr Fiala very likely to lead a new government together with another opposition alliance.
As Fiala said, "People have had enough of populists," and they want "normal, competent, and decent politics."
The opposition in Hungary will also prepare a unified election list for the parliamentary elections next year and send a single candidate to run for prime minister.
Of course, the Czech Republic still maintains a democratic system, so Babiš is preparing to join the opposition forces.
But toppling Putin is far more difficult, and it is not hard to predict that there will be more measures aimed at dismantling the Communist Party comprehensively.
But these actions also pose risks to the Kremlin.
The current situation is that the president claims that Russian democracy "has not died," and points to the country still having an "active opposition" as evidence, which suggests he at least still has an interest in pretending that Russia is not heading toward near-totalitarianism.
Putin says he only wants stability.
But his regime is pushing Russia toward a more turbulent situation.
If the Kremlin, like it does with Russian liberals, inconsistently creates and implements rules, driving the Communist Party underground, then social explosion is more likely to occur.
And if it decides no longer to suppress them, the Russian Communists — yes, the Communists — could become an undeniable force.
